annotation.TEXT: This ? block contains a cape feather. It's a little tricky to hit without the yellow switch active, but it still shouldn't be too difficult to get.
There's a timed lift, which could be useful later, but not right now.
Hi, Yoshi!
So, this room consists of random Bullet Bills, some Fuzzies, and some water hazards, which'll make you take a one-stroke penalty if you're not careful.
So, I hope you all enjoyed watching me play through 4 RESWOB FO YELLAV! Now, before I end the video, let's stomp one of those switch palace switches, just for fun!
By the way, I'll just quickly show that this pipe is two-way. The pipes themselves couldn't be changed, but the secondary entrances could.
Well, I'm here for the normal exit right now. Of course, it's probably obvious what must be done to reach the secret exit, but I'll get to that later.
Okay, so once you have Yoshi, go back this way. Being super so that you can tear through these turn blocks is really helpful.
Anyway, I'm supposed to go left to reach my level, but what if I tried going right instead?
Gah! I hate it when that happens when I'm totally expecting to bounce off of the duder I'm spin jumping on!
Make absolutely sure Yoshi does not swallow the key, of course. It would suck for that to happen, forcing you to redo most of this.
Now, adjusting the time limit was another thing you could do, so I increased this level's time limit from 300 to 500 seconds to give the player ample time for all of this.
...SomeGuy712x's entry for SMW Central's 8th 24HR thing!
BGM: DKC2 - In a Snow-Bound Land
Why did I do that? Now the key is stuck with the Mega Mole. I should be able to retrieve it, though.
Alright, and now both Yoshi and the key are up here with me!
Oh, and since I Start+Selected out of the level to show off the midpoint entrance, all of these duders back here have respawned.
You see, Yoshi can't climb vines (This isn't Toadette Strikes), so you could just leave Yoshi behind here, and take the key on your own from this point forward.
Wait, Pokey? ...Ohh... That's right. I was testing something for somebody involving a star kill being worth more points than expected, so I added a Pokey, a slope, and a ? block with a star here.

And there we go. That's the normal exit. Hmm... Maybe I should've had the bullet generator stop here, but it's okay, since the bullets can't harm Mario during the victory march. (However, if you have Yoshi, it's entirely possible for the bullets to knock you off of him, which is kind of a bummer.)
I'm going to do mostly the same things until I reach Yoshi, so don't expect many annotations until then.
Watch out for the Chucks, sliding Koopa, and fish here. (Well, you can safely ignore the fish.)
D'oh! Screwed that up. Also, the sound effect for my reserve item being released sounded kind of funny.
There's yet another power up here. Yeah, I've been pretty generous with the power ups.
You could also do a few other things, such as change your starting point. I've put a link to the contest's rules page in the description, in case you want more details.
Well, at least the key wasn't in Yoshi's mouth at the time, but that still sucks.
Huh, I wonder why I normal stomped that shell while trying to slide-kill it there. I was sliding when it hit me...
Whoa, no! Not again! YOSHIIIII!!!!!
I have a cape, so I'm flying here.

So, yeah. I've gotta check the pipes. Now, the pipes are objects and can't be changed, and that includes whether they're exit-enabled or not, so there's really only one pipe I need to check, and that's the pipe that was enterable in the original VoB4.
Anyway, there's the secret exit, which unlocks the path to the Yellow Switch Palace.
Now, let me get that gray platform to respawn...
There's midpoint, and the midpoint entrance does work correctly, although I moved the midpoint entrance slightly.
Okay, enough with being sidetracked here. Let's get to the main stuff. Now, Yoshi's House has been renamed "B AND Y SWITCHES", because...
Hello, and welcome to...
Yeah, by just waiting on the middle of the turn block bridge on the right, that disco shell will just roast itself. Also, there's another shell-kicker to beware of here as well.
BGM: Street Fighter 2 - Guile's Theme

I may as well explain my discovery. If the last enemy you killed before collecting a star was slide-killed, and you don't do anything that would reset your star-kill combo immediately afterwards, your first star-kill will be worth 400 instead of 200.
Heads up!
Yeah, so I moved the starting point all the way over here, beyond the goal posts. However, the goal tape is a sprite, and can therefore be removed, which is what I've done.
Everything can be shell-killed except for the spiked balls, so bringing a shell in with you can help. Also, everything's edible, so bringing Yoshi can help even more!
Alright, for making it this far, you're rewarded with a 1-up and a hint.
The YSP's name has been changed to "THANKS FOR PLAYING!", but the level itself is unchanged.
Whoa! Yeah, there's another shell-kicker right there that you gotta watch out for. Now, don't rush forward too fast while crossing the next lava pit.
I'm not gonna bother trying for the 1-up combo here again, though.
Yep, I haven't forgotten about that key. However, I'm not gonna go for the secret exit right now.
Demo count: 1
Sacrificial horse count: 1
Oh, this is a good time for me to show you guys exactly where the midpoint entrance is. (Also, I just noticed that my score is exactly 77770 right now. Purely coincidental!)
This room isn't very long, and reaching the power up block should ensure that you reach the goal.

I think what happens is, slide-killing a duder sets your current star-kill combo to exactly 1 kill, the 200-point one, so doing this can give you a slight head-start on your next star-kill combo, I guess. Who knows why it was programmed that way, though...
Yeah, it's obviously "VALLEY OF BOWSER 4" backwards, and I named it that way, because...
Alright, now it's time to go for the secret exit.
Huh. Why was that shell-kicker was going the other way there? I honestly don't know.
Sacrificial horse count: 2
Now, just like in the original VoB4, you'll need Yoshi to get the key. However, the keyhole isn't right here with the key this time!
Unfortunately, Mega Mole is neither flammable nor inflammable. You can eat him from here, of course, but if you're able to do so, that likely means that disco is dead.
I just realized that I forgot to change 4 RESWOB FO YELLAV's level dot to red on the overworld. Oh, well. The OW wasn't judged in this contest anyway.

So, yeah. The level I chose for this contest was Valley of Bowser 4, and there are a few yellow and blue ! blocks in that level, which are objects, and thus can't be moved or deleted. So, I put these switches here in case players wanted those blocks filled.
Removing a few key turn blocks here will help.
Alright, just don't do anything stupid, like get Yoshi boiled again...

So, anyway, the gist of this contest is that we had to pick a level from a select few, remove all of its existing sprites, and place new sprites down to create a different experience. You had to leave all of the level's objects exactly as they were, though.
Close call there. I almost didn't manage to stomp that green Parakoopa.
Let's move on.
Hi, Yoshi! I'll try not to boil you in lava this time!
Toasty! Alright, let's grab the key and make our way all the way back to the left side of the level.
Silly Chuck.
Wow, I got sloppy there! That's okay, though. With this flower and the nearby feather, I can quickly get back up to full strength.
...I put these two switch palace switches here! (Maybe I should've called this place "Y AND B SWITCHES" instead, because the yellow switch is on the left. Oh, well.)

There's a timed lift which is once again helpful for backtracking, and makes it easier to collect this 1-up as well. In addition, the blue Koopa will let Yoshi fly, allowing you to go back for the key much more easily!
Bonk! 400 from the very first star-kill there. And the next star-kills will be worth 800, then 1000, and so on (not counting Chucks, which are always worth 800 and don't count towards the combo).
There's a flower, but it's guarded by a Chuck trio. However, you can use this handy dandy Koopa to easily dispatch them.

Yeah, there's a Mega Mole there. He's pretty much harmless, but his presence prevents Yoshi from easily eating the disco shell. (However, you could kill the Mega Mole with the Koopa that I had Yoshi eat here.)
Another thing you could do is leave Yoshi behind as soon as you retrieve the key. And actually, you're almost forced to leave Yoshi behind up ahead anyway.
Yeah, this is just an unedited YI2, so there's really nothing to see here.
Now, for this next part, I tossed in a growing vine sprite so that you can easily climb up and continue on with the level.
BGM: Castlevania - Vampire Killer
Alright, remember this timed lift? Well, now is when it's useful.
I'm not going to hit either of those switches right now, though. Alright, now it's time for our feature presentation, which is... "4 RESWOB FO YELLAV"?
However, I'm intentionally not flying with the blue shell, just to show that it's easily possible to backtrack without it. (Maybe I should've left it alive for later, though.)
Strike!

Yep, that's where the midpoint entrance is. Also, that's why I had the player start on a turn block bridge at the beginning of the level. I needed the level entrance to be one tile above the ground there so that the player wouldn't fall through the floor when starting from the midpoint entrance.
Ow, my coccyx!
...You start at the end, and have to work your way through the level backwards!
BGM: Final Fantasy IV - Victory
However, did you really think I was really going to leave Yoshi behind here? Nah. There's actually a few ways to get Yoshi up here.
These timed lifts are handy for backtracking. Alright, here's the pipe I need to enter.
BGM: Sonic & Knuckles - Lava Reef Zone, Act 1
You can cape fly up, but that might be a little tricky. You can ulitize the blue Koopa that was here, but I kinda boiled him, so that option's out now. So, I'll try something else.
Heck, yeah! 1-life combo!
Aha! Now I could fly up much more easily, but I think I'll take the turn block "elevator" instead.
See y'all later!
Wah! Oh, no! ...Well, bye, Yoshi!
Alright, let's just start a new file here.
Whoa, should've taken the upper route there.
